\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Many edits were made to preserve clarity. Clarity is GOD. Clarity is something that beginners in any artform don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t quite get, because they aren\u8217\'92t used to looking at their own work with objective eyes. You need to work reallll hard on maintaining clarity of thought and expression. Once you\u8217\'92ve got a good sense for how clear your writing is, you can experiment with more poetic turns of phrase and structure. For example: the transition from \u8220\'93Bart?\u8221\'94 -> \u8220\'93The last turning the pang into a bottomless pit.\u8221\'94 A clearer version: \u8220\'93Bart? This last name turned the pang into a bottomless pit.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Also: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91Black hole\u8217\'92/ \u8216\'91pang of sorrow\u8217\'92 / \u8216\'91swallowing abyss\u8217\'92 - these are basic/default descriptors for a character struggling with depression. It\u8217\'92s something a middle schooler would write. You need to dig deeper. I\u8217\'92ve tried to just put a basic twist on it so it\u8217\'92s not so transparent.}
